Problem
A team of professionals working in the field of Work Psychology has requested your collaboration for data analysis. The team collected information on a sample of 300 employees from a company that provides technological solutions to small and medium-sized businesses. One of their main interests is to identify predictors of job satisfaction and employee performance based on demographic, organizational, and clinical variables. Additionally, they seek your assistance in analyzing possible associations, correlations, and significant differences considering specific variables.

4. Create a contingency table for the variables Job_type and Female_gender and analyze whether there is an association between these variables. Interpret and report the results.

con1 <- table(BaseTrabajo$Tipo_de_trabajo,BaseTrabajo$Genero_femenino)
addmargins(prop.table(con1))
##      
##                0          1        Sum
##   1   0.06666667 0.07666667 0.14333333
##   2   0.19666667 0.16000000 0.35666667
##   3   0.11000000 0.06666667 0.17666667
##   4   0.20333333 0.12000000 0.32333333
##   Sum 0.57666667 0.42333333 1.00000000
chisq.test(con1)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  con1
## X-squared = 4.0131, df = 3, p-value = 0.26

Since both variables are qualitative and all groups have frequencies above 5%, a chi-square test was conducted. No association was observed between job type and gender (p = .26). There is evidence supporting the independence of these variables.

Final report

A multiple regression analysis was conducted to assess the effects of cognitive flexibility, work environment perception, self-esteem, future job outlook, anxiety, depression, and intelligence on job satisfaction. The results indicated that these predictors had a significant effect on job satisfaction (F(6,239)=525.9, p < .001). Specifically, an increase of one unit in cognitive flexibility was associated with an increase of 0.92 units in job satisfaction, while a one-unit increase in work environment perception was associated with a decrease of 0.75 units in job satisfaction. Additionally, higher self-esteem was linked to a decrease of 0.34 units in job satisfaction, while a positive outlook on future job opportunities led to an increase of 1.32 units. Anxiety showed a negative association, with a one-unit increase correlating with a 0.58-unit decrease in job satisfaction, while depression was associated with a 0.67-unit increase in satisfaction. All model parameters were found to be significant, with an adjusted R of 0.91 and a predictive capacity of 92%, explaining 92% of the variance in job satisfaction. The model also met the criteria for parsimony, maintaining an optimal number of predictors.
A multiple regression model was also constructed to determine the best predictors of employee performance (Rendimiento). The analysis utilized an automatic selection method, considering all variables, excluding the ID. The final model was optimized by excluding non-significant predictors, such as anxiety and intelligence, based on the principle of parsimony, which aims to retain the most efficient model with fewer predictors. The evaluation of multicollinearity showed no issues, as all Variance Inflation Factors (VIFs) were below 10.
The models performance was assessed using the ROC curve, which demonstrated a value of 0.99, indicating excellent predictive accuracy. Further evaluation revealed that the model correctly predicted positive cases (sensitivity) 97.89% of the time and negative cases (specificity) 91.14% of the time.
In terms of the odds ratios, the analysis showed that increasing work environment perception by 12 points resulted in an increase of 5034.12 times in the likelihood of satisfactory performance. Additionally, a 10-point increase in job satisfaction increased the likelihood by 177.52 times, while a 15-point increase in cognitive flexibility decreased the likelihood by 89 times. Employees in customer service and sales were found to have 94 times less chance of satisfactory performance compared to those in marketing when controlling for other variables.
These findings highlight key predictors that significantly influence employee job satisfaction and performance, offering valuable insights for organizational strategies and improving employee well-being and productivity.
